2011</DATE><ITEM>Working on checking sources; focused mainly on Bailey&apos;s text &quot;Three Queer Lives&quot;</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>13 September 2011</DATE><ITEM>Still working on CAS. Almost checked all of Paul Bailey&apos;s &quot;Three Queer Lives&quot;</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>14 September 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>19 September 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>20 September 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>21 September 2011</DATE><ITEM>In process of reviewing punctuation and spacing; using delivery as a visual guide. I am up to &apos;Ripon and Elsewhere&apos;.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>23 September 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>26 September 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>28 September 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>28 September 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>29 September 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>29 September 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>5 October 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>5 October 2011</DATE><ITEM>This is now cas c.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="NPA" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>24 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>25 November 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft c, rbv c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFB" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>6 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>cfb c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>8 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft i</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>12 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft c, pilot 43</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>12 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>13 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>13 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY WORKSTATUS="pub" RESP="MPO" WORKVALUE="c"><DATE>16 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub c pilot43</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY></REVISIONDESC></ORLANDOHEADER><DIV0><HEADING>Biography</HEADING><STANDARD>Jacob, Naomi</STANDARD><DIV1><PERSONNAME><DIV2><DATASTRUCT><DATAITEM><BIRTHNAME WROTEORPUBLISHEDAS="WROTEPUBLISHEDASYES" REG="Jacob, Naomi"><GIVEN>Naomi</GIVEN><GIVEN>Eleanor</GIVEN><GIVEN>Claire</GIVEN><SURNAME>Jacob</SURNAME></BIRTHNAME></DATAITEM><DATAITEM><INDEXED INDEXSOURCE="BL">Naomi Ellington Jacob</INDEXED><SCHOLARNOTE><P>Most standard library catalogues list her (in 2011) under this name.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></DATAITEM><DATAITEM><PSEUDONYM WROTEORPUBLISHEDAS="WROTEPUBLISHEDASYES" NAMESIGNIFIER="CRYPTIC" REG="Gray, Ellington">Ellington Gray</PSEUDONYM></DATAITEM><DATAITEM><NICKNAME NAMETYPE="FAMILIAR" NAMECONNOTATION="ABUSIVE" NAMESIGNIFIER="LOCAL" REG="Micky">Micky or Mickie</NICKNAME>, <NICKNAME NAMETYPE="FAMILIAR" NAMECONNOTATION="HONORIFIC" REG="La Signora Micky">La Signora Micky</NICKNAME><SCHOLARNOTE><P>Yorksire people believed, when NJ was growing up, that Irish seasonal workers were dirty, so as a frequently grubby child she was called a <SOCALLED>proper Mick</SOCALLED>, and the name stuck, even in Italy.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 42" DBREF="68825">42</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 79" DBREF="68930">79</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SCHOLARNOTE></DATAITEM><DATAITEM><NICKNAME NAMETYPE="FAMILIAR">Jacob</NICKNAME>, <NICKNAME NAMETYPE="FAMILIAR">Jake</NICKNAME><SCHOLARNOTE><P>In contexts of work or politics she was often known as Jacob or even Jake.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 138, 199" DBREF="68825">138, 199</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SCHOLARNOTE></DATAITEM></DATASTRUCT></DIV2></PERSONNAME></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Birth and Influences</HEADING><BIRTH><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="SYS"><DATE VALUE="1884-07-01" CERTAINTY="CERT">1 July 1884</DATE><CHRONPROSE><BIRTHPOSITION POSITION="ELDEST">NJ was born at <PLACE><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE>20 High St Agnes Gate</ADDRLINE></ADDRESS>, <SETTLEMENT>Ripon</SETTLEMENT>, in <REGION>Yorkshire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, the elder of two sisters.</BIRTHPOSITION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>According to her own account of her birth written sixty-four years later, her father had wanted a boy and reacted to her appearance with anger and disgust. Her exhausted, unhappy mother expressed equal disgust, while only her Jewish grandfather welcomed the baby and blessed her in Yiddish.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 77" DBREF="68930">77</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></BIRTH></DIV1><DIV1><CULTURALFORMATION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ was born, with <ETHNICITY SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" FOREBEAR="FATHER" REG="Jewish">Jewish</ETHNICITY> and <NATIONALHERITAGE FOREBEAR="GRANDPARENTS">Polish</NATIONALHERITAGE>/<NATIONALHERITAGE FOREBEAR="FATHER" SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES">German</NATIONALHERITAGE> heritage, into an <NATIONALITY SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="English">English</NATIONALITY>, <GEOGHERITAGE><PLACE><REGION>Yorkshire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE></GEOGHERITAGE> milieu. Although both parents worked, then or later, in <CLASS>professional</CLASS> occupations they were not wealthy, and even less so after the father lost his job. NJ was brought up as an <DENOMINATION SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="Anglican"><ORGNAME STANDARD="Anglican Church">Anglican</ORGNAME></DENOMINATION>, became a <DENOMINATION SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="Roman Catholic"><ORGNAME STANDARD="Roman Catholic Church">Roman Catholic</ORGNAME></DENOMINATION> convert at about the age of thirty, and grew to hate her father. It was as a practising Catholic that she visited a war-weary but triumphantly independent Ireland in the 1920s.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 156-9" DBREF="68825">156-9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2><RACEANDETHNICITY><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Hating her father, idealizing her paternal grandfather, identifying strongly with her mother&apos;s Yorkshire people, NJ reflects in her writings deeply conflicted views about her <ETHNICITY SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" FOREBEAR="FATHER" REG="Jewish">Jewish</ETHNICITY> side. She regularly and proudly asserted it as part of her identity and related triumphant put-downs she had allegedly scored against antisemitism. Yet her non-Jewish novels depict innumerable stereotypical crass, loud, or dirty Jewish characters as well as a number of strikingly idealized Jews, and the same mixture is observable in her series about the Jewish-immigrant Gollantz family.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></RACEANDETHNICITY><SEXUALITY><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ discovered her own <SEXUALIDENTITY SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="lesbian">lesbianism</SEXUALIDENTITY> when she saw <NAME>Marguerite Broadfoote</NAME> performing at the <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Middlesbrough</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Yorkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> <ORGNAME STANDARD="Middlesbrough Theatre">Empire</ORGNAME>. She claimed, however, that the reason she dressed in men&apos;s clothes was in order to save money. Her sexuality (well known among her circle of friends) is not reflected in her writings, and was for many years ignored by standard reference sources although her earliest biographer, <NAME>James Norbury</NAME>, did refer to it.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 102ff, 147-8" DBREF="68930">102ff, 147-48</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></SEXUALITY></CULTURALFORMATION></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="MOTHER"><DIV2><HEADING>Mother</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ&apos;s mother was born <NAME STANDARD="Collinson, Nana">Selina Sara Ellington Collinson</NAME> and generally (from childhood) known as Nana. She resumed her birth name after leaving her husband<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 79" DBREF="68930">79</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and <JOB REG="writer">wrote journalism and some novels</JOB> under the name of <NAME STANDARD="Collinson, Nana"><SOCALLED>Nina Abbott</SOCALLED></NAME>. Her family had been rooted as yeomen on the same spot in <PLACE><REGION>Yorkshire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> for three hundred years. Nana, in NJ&apos;s portrayal, was the eldest of three children whose mother died young after a romantic elopement. She resented her father&apos;s second marriage, longed for education and a career, and made a hasty, unhappy marriage while still in her teens, for obscure and confused reasons, since sexual attraction was certainly not among them. She found her wedding night rough, even brutal, and became aware of her husband&apos;s philandering only a few weeks into the marriage.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 71, 73, 74, 75" DBREF="68930">71, 73, 74, 75</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 36-7" DBREF="68825">36-7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>She was not yet twenty-one when her elder daughter was born. Naomi felt that her mother exerted a crucial influence over her life, handing on to her the key qualities of literary talent and rebelliousness.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Trefusis, dustjacket" DBREF="12369">dustjacket</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>She describes her mother as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">in advance of her times in many ways</QUOTE>: a bicycle rider, a Poor Law Guardian,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 38" DBREF="68825">38</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> witty, charming, deeply religious, but with no money and no idea how to deal with money. Nana read <NAME STANDARD="Shaw, George Bernard">Shaw</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Mrs Warren&apos;s Profession</TITLE> (which was written to draw attention to prostitution) when it was regarded as almost unmentionably scandalous.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 40, 42" DBREF="68825">40, 42</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She taught Naomi to read and never talked down to her, and though she monitored her daughter&apos;s reading she forbade nothing that was worthwhile.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 286" DBREF="68825">286</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> After causing surprise by calling a young Mrs Robinson <SOCALLED>Perdita</SOCALLED>, she offered <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a sketch of <NAME STANDARD="Robinson, Mary">Perdita, Mrs. Robinson</NAME>, even to quoting the Memoirs of <NAME STANDARD="Hawkins, Laetitia-Matilda">someone called Miss Hawkins</NAME> who wrote of her.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 177" DBREF="68825">177</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>Hawkins, in her memoirs of 1824, was remarkable in discerning courage and virtue in Robinson&apos;s life of hard literary work, despite her reputation as a fallen woman.</P></SCHOLARNOTE> When she left her husband, Nana got herself a job as <JOB REG="hotel manager">manageress of a hotel</JOB>. She seems to have more or less abandoned her elder daughter, then teenaged, when she <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="emigrant">emigrated</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> to the <PLACE><GEOG>USA</GEOG></PLACE> (often forgetting to send the allowance she had promised) though Naomi insisted that she had been offered the chance to go with her mother and sister to America and had refused. Nana visited England, and Naomi, within a few years, and moved back to England in 1918. About a year after NJ&apos;s move to Italy her mother joined her there for what turned out to be the last winter of her life.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 88, 100-1, 143-7" DBREF="68930">88, 100-1, 143-7</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 49-50" DBREF="68825">49-50</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>NJ&apos;s earliest memoir describes many relations, almost all of them Yorkshire folk from her mother&apos;s side.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 33-8" DBREF="68825">33-8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER><MEMBER RELATION="GRANDFATHER"><DIV2><HEADING>Maternal Grandfather</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ&apos;s maternal grandfather, <NAME>Robert Ellington Collinson</NAME>, a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">die-hard</QUOTE> Tory,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 189" DBREF="68825">189</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <JOB CURRENTALTERNATIVETERM="hotel manager" REG="hotel keeper">kept a hotel</JOB> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Ripon</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Yorkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> and was a <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>magistrate</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> and an <JOB>alderman</JOB>, but he was also a <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>drinker, gambler, and avid theatre-goer</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>. After his wife, NJ&apos;s grandmother, died young, he married again and had a second family.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 70-2" DBREF="68930">70-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER><MEMBER RELATION="FOREBEAR"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>A great-great-uncle of NJ was alleged to have become <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">unbelievably rich</QUOTE> as <JOB>Master of the Horse</JOB> to the Cham of Tartary, and to have returned home bringing with him two of his seven wives.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 190" DBREF="68825">190</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER><MEMBER RELATION="FATHER"><DIV2><HEADING>Father</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ&apos;s father, <NAME>Samuel Jacob</NAME>, had started life in <PLACE><GEOG>Germany</GEOG></PLACE>, the country to which his father had fled as a boy from <PLACE><GEOG>Poland</GEOG></PLACE>, after <EMPH>his</EMPH> parents were killed in pogroms. Longer ago still, his forebears had been driven from <PLACE><GEOG>Spain</GEOG></PLACE> to <PLACE><GEOG REG="Netherlands">Holland</GEOG></PLACE> and from Holland to Poland. Samuel converted early from <ORGNAME>Judaism</ORGNAME> to <ORGNAME>Christianity</ORGNAME> (evangelical <ORGNAME STANDARD="Anglican Church">Anglicanism</ORGNAME>) and as a school-leaver in England, soon to go to university, he received advice from <NAME STANDARD="Disraeli, Benjamin">Disraeli</NAME> on the duty of work. He became a <JOB>teacher</JOB>, then (just before his marriage) <JOB>headmaster</JOB> of the <ORGNAME REG="Minster High School,, Ripon">Minster Choir School</ORGNAME> at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Ripon</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Yorkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, but he lost this position when Naomi was about eight, because of his <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>drinking and chasing women</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 189-90" DBREF="68825">189-90</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 73, 75-6" DBREF="68930">73, 75-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> His daughter, who grew to hate him, said he was a <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>womaniser</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> and a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Teutonic</QUOTE> bully,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268" QTDIN="QTDINYES"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> even about details of no importance. Different commentators have identified him as the model from which she portrayed both <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">brutish Yorkshire husbands</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and Jewish characters who deny their roots while bringing them into disrepute by affecting ultra-Englishness.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Furbank 8" DBREF="10711">8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> NJ learned much that she had never known about her father during the winter that her mother spent with her in Italy.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 145" DBREF="68930">145</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER><MEMBER RELATION="GRANDFATHER"><DIV2><HEADING>Paternal Grandfather</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ&apos;s paternal grandfather, <NAME>Samson Jacob</NAME>,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 74" DBREF="68930">74</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a little man, with snow-white hair</QUOTE>, and an exceptionally gentle manner, but he was as die-hard a Tory as her other grandfather, the Yorkshire squire.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 189" DBREF="68825">189</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> An uncle had rescued him when his parents died by barbarous violence in a Russian pogrom in <PLACE><GEOG>Poland</GEOG></PLACE>; he had reached England as a young man, <JOB REG="tailor">built a tailoring business from nothing</JOB>, become a naturalized Englishman and acquired some English language. He reverted to Yiddish in moments of emotion, for which his son would sternly reprove him.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 76" DBREF="68930">76</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER><MEMBER RELATION="SISTER"><DIV2><HEADING>Sister</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>Naomi&apos;s younger sister, called <NAME>Muriel Godsell</NAME> after her marriage, was a gentle, meek girl quite unlike her elder. She had children with a husband who died during the second world war.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 82-3, 86, 143" DBREF="68930">82-3, 86, 143</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><VIOLENCE><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ never forgot the terror and indignity of having her father pull down her drawers and hit her on the bare bottom during her childhood.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 81-2" DBREF="68930">81-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></VIOLENCE></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><HEADING>Ripon and Elsewhere</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>Jacob begins her earliest book of memoirs by laying emphasis on the fact that she lived her first eleven years in <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a Yorkshire town of great antiquity</QUOTE> (<PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Ripon</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Yorkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>),<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 21" DBREF="68825">21</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and the county pervades the opening section of the book. She devotes pages to its ancient traditions and to Yorkshire humour, with anecdotes in dialect.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 22-30" DBREF="68825">22-30</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">fine, upstanding spirit</QUOTE> found in Yorkshire homes, she writes, is not only that of the county but that of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">real England</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 30" DBREF="68825">30</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Only after that does she move on to anecdotes of a personal kind, which often branch off into further Yorkshire lore.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION><LOCATION RELATIONTO="MOVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>When she was eight her Ripon years were marked by a move from the beloved <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Old House,, Ripon">Old House</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="Ripon"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Yorkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> (with a large garden) to a tall, modern house which she disliked.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 80, 85" DBREF="68930">80, 85</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>The real break came when her mother left her father and moved her daughters to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Whitby</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Yorkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, with a stay at a farm near <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Malton</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Yorkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> until their new home was ready. Later they moved to other jobs and other lodgings, about whose location NJ is often vague or contradictory. These places included <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Manchester</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Lancashire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> (whose industrial grime came as a shock) and <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>High Wycombe</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Buckinghamshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, perhaps along with other towns in the south of England.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 87-8, 92" DBREF="68930">87-8, 92</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Education</HEADING><EDUCATION MODE="INSTITUTIONAL"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ attended a number of private schools, the first of which was within walking distance of her home. <CONTESTEDBEHAVIOUR>The <SCHOOL INSTITUTION="PRIVATE" INSTITUTIONLEVEL="PRIMARY">school</SCHOOL> she next attended was run by two ladies who asked her to leave, and from her next school she often played truant. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 82, 85-6" DBREF="68930">82, 85-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CONTESTEDBEHAVIOUR> A better school, in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Whitby</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Yorkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, covered exclusively England in its <SUBJECT>history</SUBJECT> syllabus,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 88" DBREF="68930">88</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and disappointed Naomi by the emphasis it laid on <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">fancy-work and <SUBJECT>needlework</SUBJECT>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 43" DBREF="68825">43</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Then came the <ORGNAME STANDARD="City of Leeds School"><SCHOOL INSTITUTION="STATE" INSTITUTIONLEVEL="SECONDARY" REG="City of Leeds School">Central Higher Grade School</SCHOOL></ORGNAME> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Leeds</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Yorkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> (the city&apos;s first state-run secondary school&mdash;later the City of Leeds School&mdash;<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Open Plaques" DBREF="69187"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS>which her mother chose, she said, out of some <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">sudden spasm of acute democracy</QUOTE>).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 44" DBREF="68825">44</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Leeds was important to her because she there first attended the theatre.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 45-6" DBREF="68825">45-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> According to her own account, she next went to<PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Middlesbrough</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Yorkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> <ORGNAME STANDARD="Middlesbrough High School"><SCHOOL INSTITUTION="BOARDING" STUDENTBODY="SINGLESEX" INSTITUTIONLEVEL="SECONDARY" REG="Middlesbrough High School">High School</SCHOOL></ORGNAME> (<QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a prestigious boarding school</QUOTE>),<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 91" DBREF="68930">91</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> then to be subjected to more fancy-work, <SUBJECT REG="music">piano</SUBJECT>, and <SUBJECT REG="Bible study">Scripture</SUBJECT> at a <SCHOOL INSTITUTION="PRIVATE" STUDENTBODY="SINGLESEX" INSTITUTIONLEVEL="SECONDARY">small, select school</SCHOOL> near <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Wantage</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Oxfordshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> (or it might, in some of her other accounts, have been <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Taunton</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Somerset"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>), from which she ran away. She was fifteen, and this was the end of her schooling (she was left ignorant of such basics as <SUBJECT>arithmetic</SUBJECT>, <SUBJECT>grammar</SUBJECT>, and <SUBJECT>geography</SUBJECT>), since her mother then decided to emigrate to the USA with her sister, and Naomi declined to go with her. This is her own first account of the matter, and her later accounts differ from it only slightly. The <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Oxford Dictionary of National Biography</TITLE> (which omits the question of Wantage) suggests that she left school at Middlesbrough for financial reasons.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 92-3" DBREF="68930">92-3</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 48-9" DBREF="68825">48-9</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></EDUCATION><EDUCATION MODE="DOMESTIC"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>One of NJ&apos;s favourite home occupations even as a small child was improvised <SUBJECT REG="drama">acting</SUBJECT>, with her sister in spear-carrying roles. She also learned <SUBJECT>cricket</SUBJECT> and <SUBJECT>football</SUBJECT>, and her grandfather Collinson taught her <SUBJECT>whist</SUBJECT>. She mentions many books that she loved in childhood: <TEXT><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Swiss Family Robinson</TITLE> by <NAME>Johann David Wyss</NAME></TEXT>, <TEXT>fairy-tales by <NAME STANDARD="Andersen, Hans Christian">Hans Andersen</NAME> and the <NAME STANDARD="Grimm, Jacob Ludwig Carl">brothers</NAME> <NAME STANDARD="Grimm, Wilhelm Carl">Grimm</NAME></TEXT>, and <TEXT>boys&apos; adventure stories</TEXT>. By her teen years she had graduated to <TEXT><NAME>Marie Corelli</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Sorrows of Satan</TITLE></TEXT>. When she was a downtrodden pupil-teacher in Middlesbrough, the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Middlesbrough Free Library">Free Library</ORGNAME> became personally important to her.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 82-5" DBREF="68930">82-5</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 31, 51-2" DBREF="68825">31, 51-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></EDUCATION><EDUCATION MODE="INSTITUTIONAL"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>The library must have helped her to study hard, pass an exam which she calls the <AWARD AWARDTYPE="SCHOLARSHIP">King&apos;s Scholarship</AWARD>, and win her teaching qualification. She later achieved the <DEGREE>Elementary School Teachers&apos; Certificate</DEGREE>, and other certificates for <SUBJECT>teaching</SUBJECT> particular subjects. Some of her studying was done at the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Newlands Convent,, Cleveland">Newlands Convent</ORGNAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 53, 57" DBREF="68825">53, 57</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></EDUCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Teaching, the Stage</HEADING><OCCUPATION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>After she left school at fifteen and her mother emigrated to America, NJ became a <JOB REG="teacher">pupil-teacher</JOB> at a <EMPLOYER>church school in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Middlesbrough</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Yorkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE></EMPLOYER> <REMUNERATION>at a salary of twelve pounds a year</REMUNERATION>. She boarded in the house of some church people, and was miserable, lonely, and poor. The children, even poorer, were many of them barefoot and dirty; she felt the discipline was far too rigid and the teaching dominated by the learning of lists. She became a good teacher, she felt, by refusing to do it in the way that was expected of her. But even this did not exempt her from constant criticism of her personal demeanour and habits (her smoking, for instance, was disapproved as <SOCALLED>unsexed</SOCALLED>).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 49-50, 52-5, 60" DBREF="68825">49-50, 52-5, 60</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <REMUNERATION>Once properly certificated she earned <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">something like &pound;70 a year</QUOTE> with annual increments of five pounds.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 57" DBREF="68825">57</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></REMUNERATION></P><P>She was then invited to work as <JOB REG="secretary">secretary</JOB> (<JOB REG="personal assistant">booking travel, answering letters</JOB>) by the variety actress <EMPLOYER><NAME>Marguerite Broadfoote</NAME></EMPLOYER>. <REMUNERATION>NJ hated to lose her pension</REMUNERATION> and feared for her respectability (Broadfoote appeared on stage in tights), but in the end advice against taking up this offer led to her losing her temper and accepting it.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 67-8" DBREF="68825">67-8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She found she loved hard work without set hours, as Broadfoote&apos;s <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">friend, her secretary, her adviser, and in many ways her <JOB REG="theatrical manager">manager</JOB>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 69" DBREF="68825">69</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>After the First World War she became a <JOB HISTORICALTERM="actress" REG="acting">performer</JOB> herself, a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">character woman</QUOTE>. <REMUNERATION>She relates an anecdote of foiling an attempt to get her services for nine pounds a week when she had been promised twelve.</REMUNERATION><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 92" DBREF="68825">92</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She often played charwomen, particularly drunken ones; yet she was rejected for one such part because she refused to show her ankles at the audition. She once rejected the part of Lady Isabel in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">East Lynne</TITLE> (touring version adapted from the adaptation of <NAME>Ellen Wood</NAME>&apos;s novel) because <SOCALLED>heavies</SOCALLED> were not her thing.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 95, 160" DBREF="68825">95, 160</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><LEISUREANDSOCIETY><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>She mentions theatre-going as a highlight of her time in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Leeds</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Yorkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> (attending school) and concerts as a highlight of her time in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Middlesbrough</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Yorkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> (as a pupil-teacher).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 45-8, 54" DBREF="68825">45-8, 54</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LEISUREANDSOCIETY></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="MOVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>When, after her time in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Leeds</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Yorkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> and longer time in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Middlesbrough</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Yorkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, NJ moved to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> to work for <NAME>Marguerite Broadfoote</NAME>, she travelled weekly with Broadfoote to whatever town she was due to perform at. When the first world war broke, Broadfoote paid for London lodgings for Jacob, so that the latter might do the war work which her own health was not up to.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 67, 69, 121" DBREF="68825">67, 69, 121</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION><LOCATION RELATIONTO="VISITED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Several times the pair spent a couple of months of the summer at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Selsey</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Sussex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, in a bungalow made of railway carriages.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 119" DBREF="68825">119</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>On the outbreak of war NJ established herself in a small flat off the <PLACE><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE>Edgware Road</ADDRLINE></ADDRESS> in <SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>. She later lived in another flat, not far away in <PLACE><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE>Baker Street</ADDRLINE></ADDRESS><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 114, 143" DBREF="68930">114, 143</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEALTH ISSUE="PHYSICAL"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>After a few years of teaching NJ (who as a child had run through all the usual infectious diseases) found herself ill with constant colds. A friend took her to a woman doctor, <NAME>Dr Levick</NAME> (a daring thing in those days), without whom she believed that she might have died. She had started smoking as a child, and smoked brown paper or cane from woven chairs when she had no money for cigarettes. She recovered promptly, however, from a burst appendix and subsequent operation.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 60-1" DBREF="68825">60-1</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 85, 165, 100-1" DBREF="68930">85, 165, 100-1</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></HEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>People</HEADING><INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS EROTIC="EROTICPOSSIBLY"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>As well as being a significant influence in other ways, the Scottish actress <NAME>Marguerite Broadfoote</NAME> (<QUOTE DIRECT="Y">my greatest friend</QUOTE>)<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 46" DBREF="68825">46</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> was (or may have been, as the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Oxford Dictionary of National Biography">Oxford Dictionary of National Biography</TITLE> has it) NJ&apos;s first lover.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 102ff" DBREF="68930">102ff</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Broadfoote, according to Jacob, had enormous intelligence but no intellect. Her favourite books included <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Way of an Eagle</TITLE> by <NAME>Ethel M. Dell</NAME> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Poems of Passion</TITLE> by <NAME>Ella Wheeler Wilcox</NAME>. Broadefoote&apos;s husband, <NAME>Ernest Edelsten</NAME>, a theatrical agent, reminded NJ unpleasantly of her father.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 67" DBREF="68825">67</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 102-3" DBREF="68930">102-3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> At the zenith of the music-hall, Broadfoote had looks, manner, and voice, and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">was on her way to the top.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 69" DBREF="68825">69</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> But she developed bad health and died young&mdash;not before her husband had summarily ended her relationship with NJ, out of jealousy not for his wife but for their son, who had become attached to Jacob and dependent on her. Later the son, <NAME>Robert Broadfoote Edelsten</NAME>, worked for some years in Italy as NJ&apos;s secretary.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 121" DBREF="68825">121</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 114, 144" DBREF="68930">114, 144</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Marriage Prospects</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>At high-school NJ was in love with a young man who sang in a church choir. She later had a brief dalliance with another young man whose stage name was <NAME>Wilkie Warren</NAME>. While working for Broadfoote she declined a marriage proposal from an acrobat,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 48, 81" DBREF="68825">48, 81</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 101" DBREF="68930">101</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and during the first world war she declined another from a toy manufacturer whom she saw as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the German Jew of caricature.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 128" DBREF="68825">128</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="HUSBAND"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>At a time when she was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">sad and lonely and desperate,</QUOTE> (perhaps after she was separated from Broadfoote, or after Broadfoote died), NJ got married. Her friends felt the marriage was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">doomed to failure from the start,</QUOTE> and indeed she and her husband separated within a couple of weeks. His name has not been recovered.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 125" DBREF="68930" QTDIN="QTDINYES">125</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS EROTIC="EROTICNO"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>She nevertheless seriously considered once again getting married, this time to <NAME>Henry Dale Johnson</NAME>, whom she met in a TB sanatorium at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Richmond</SETTLEMENT> in <REGION>Surrey</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> and who remained a close friend.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 126, 134" DBREF="68930">126, 134</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Religion and Politics</HEADING><CULTURALFORMATION><RELIGION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Meanwhile in 1914, at a low ebb in her life, NJ converted to <ORGNAME STANDARD="Roman Catholic Church"><DENOMINATION SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="Roman Catholic">Roman Catholicism</DENOMINATION></ORGNAME>. She took instruction in the faith after reading <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Confessions of a Convert</TITLE> by <NAME STANDARD="Benson, Robert Hugh">R. H. Benson</NAME> (a homosexual whose sexuality caused him <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">lasting guilt and shame</QUOTE>).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 125" DBREF="68930">125</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></RELIGION></CULTURALFORMATION></DIV1><DIV1><POLITICS><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ began her political life as a <POLITICALAFFILIATION ACTIVISM="ACTIVISTYES" REG="Conservative">Tory</POLITICALAFFILIATION> who thought Socialism deeply shocking, like all or most of the older generation of her very mixed family. She went out canvassing at elections, urging people to vote without thinking it odd that she had no vote herself. She was converted to the <POLITICALAFFILIATION ACTIVISM="ACTIVISTYES" WOMAN-GENDERISSUE="GENDERYES" REG="suffragist">suffrage</POLITICALAFFILIATION> cause by hearing <NAME STANDARD="Billington Greig, Teresa">Teresa Billington</NAME> speak. She became a member of the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Women&apos;s Social and Political Union">Women&apos;s Social and Political Union</ORGNAME> in 1912, organized meetings, suffered physical violence, and visited London as a delegate to the first WSPU conference. She admired <NAME STANDARD="Pankhurst, Emmeline">Emmeline</NAME> and <NAME>Christabel Pankhurst</NAME>, but especially <NAME>Charlotte Despard</NAME>. She became a <POLITICALAFFILIATION ACTIVISM="ACTIVISTYES" REG="Socialist">campaigner</POLITICALAFFILIATION>, too, for the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Labour Party">Labour Party</ORGNAME>. At <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Selsey</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Sussex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, though she promised to abstain from suffrage work during the visit of an important politician, she concealed an alarm clock in a biscuit tin to simulate a bomb, and caused considerable alarm. Looking back later and anxious not to sound too earnest about a now long-distant cause, she suggested that the most valuable thing about her suffrage experience was that it had made her think.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 62-6, 119-20" DBREF="68825">62-6, 119-20</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>She later entered municipal politics in the London borough of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT CURRENT="London" REG="Marylebone">Marylebone</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, making an impassioned speech in support of the <POLITICALAFFILIATION ACTIVISM="ACTIVISTYES" REG="Socialist">Socialist</POLITICALAFFILIATION> candidate. After that she was adopted as candidate for several elections herself, but was never successful in the poll. More than once, in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Birmingham</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Warwickshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> and again in Marylebone, she was harrassed on account of her Jewish name. She says she was always a committee Socialist: weak on dates or figures, good on the topic of housing, vulnerable as a Catholic on birth control. She had been adopted as a candidate for <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Sevenoaks</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Kent"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> when she realised that her health would not allow her to stand. She wrote in her first book of memoirs about the Labour Party, with a passage on its prominent women, but at the same date, 1933, she sounded quite respectful of the one-party (<POLITICALAFFILIATION INVOLVEMENT="INVOLVEMENTNO">Fascist</POLITICALAFFILIATION>) condition of <PLACE><GEOG>Italy</GEOG></PLACE>, and the energy of <NAME STANDARD="Mussolini, Benito">Mussolini</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 189-96, 205-7" DBREF="68825">189-96, 205-7</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 132" DBREF="68930">132</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></POLITICS></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>The First World War</HEADING><OCCUPATION><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="SYS"><DATE VALUE="1914-08-06" CERTAINTY="AFTER">Later 1914</DATE><CHRONPROSE>Early in the <TOPIC>First World War</TOPIC> NJ took up <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="volunteer personnel work">volunteer work</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> for the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Women&apos;s Emergency Corps">Women&apos;s Emergency Corps</ORGNAME>, directing women into whatever work the war effort had need of.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 122, 123" DBREF="68825">122, 123</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><KEYWORDCLASS>World War I</KEYWORDCLASS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>The <ORGNAME>Women&apos;s Emergency Corps</ORGNAME> was founded by a group of women, including actresses <NAME STANDARD="Moore, Eva">Eva</NAME> and <NAME>Decima Moore</NAME> and (according to Jacob) <NAME>Gertrude Kingston</NAME>. Jacob&apos;s fellow volunteers there included <NAME STANDARD="Benson, Stella">Stella Benson</NAME> and <NAME>Viola Meynell</NAME>. NJ <JOB REG="employment agent">matched servants to employers</JOB>, <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY PHILANTHROPYVOLUNTEER="PHILANTHROPYVOLUNTEERYES" REG="charity organizer">organized flag days</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>, and went on to work for several other women&apos;s organizations, in a sequence of which her accounts remain somewhat confused. She was assigned by the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Actresses&apos; Franchise League">Actresses&apos; Franchise League</ORGNAME> to work as <JOB REG="factory secretary">secretary</JOB> for a <EMPLOYER>toy factory</EMPLOYER>. Another job was as <JOB>supervisor</JOB> or <JOB REG="manager">manager</JOB> in a <EMPLOYER>munitions factory</EMPLOYER> at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT CURRENT="London" REG="Willesden">Willesden</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, where she took the revolutionary step of engaging a woman doctor, <NAME>Grainger Evans</NAME>. NJ says too that she founded the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Three Arts Employment Fund">Three Arts Employment Fund</ORGNAME>, which organized war work for those connected with art, music, or drama. Later Jacob joined the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Women&apos;s Legion">Women&apos;s Legion</ORGNAME>, in which she became a <JOB REG="army officer">captain</JOB>. She was posted to <PLACE><GEOG>France</GEOG></PLACE>, until trench foot sent her home again.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 122, 123, 129-31, 133-8" DBREF="68825">122, 123, 129-31, 133-8</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 119, 121" DBREF="68930">119, 121</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>NJ later boasted to friends that she had <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">masqueraded</QUOTE> as a <JOB>sailor</JOB> during the first world war, and been one of the crew of a destroyer during two naval battles without having her sex suspected. Whether or not the story was true, she excluded it from her books of memoirs.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 69" DBREF="68930">69</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Postwar England</HEADING><HEALTH ISSUE="PHYSICAL"><DIV2><HEADING>Tuberculosis</HEADING><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="SYS"><DATE VALUE="1919-09-" CERTAINTY="AFTER">September 1919</DATE><CHRONPROSE>NJ entered a TB sanatorium (where the medical regime involved different levels of exercise, lots of fresh air, and no alchohol). She stayed until spring 1920, when it was declared that her tuberculosis was <SOCALLED>arrested</SOCALLED>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 122, 124" DBREF="68930">122, 124</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 138-41" DBREF="68825">138-41</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>She was a difficult and insubordinate patient. A later <SOCALLED>cure</SOCALLED> (four months at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Richmond</SETTLEMENT> in <REGION>Surrey</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> run by Dr <NAME>Harry Wadd</NAME>) featured rest, open windows, sunlight, plenty of food and permission to smoke. This was followed by five months in the <PLACE><REGION>Lake District</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 122-4, 133" DBREF="68930">122-4, 133</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 184-5" DBREF="68825">184-5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> But in 1930, NJ was advised to leave England for the sake of her health. This was her immediate reason for settling in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Sirmione"></SETTLEMENT><GEOG>Italy</GEOG></PLACE>: she says she set out the week after <NAME>Ethel Bentham</NAME>, a fellow member of the Labour Party and a highly respected doctor, persuaded her to pull out of a local political campaign for health reasons.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 196" DBREF="68825">196</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></HEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><OCCUPATION><DIV2><HEADING>Re-appearances on Stage</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>After interruptions from the war and from her first bout with tuberculosis NJ returned to <JOB HISTORICALTERM="actress" REG="acting">performing</JOB>, this time to the legitimate stage, where after a frightening initiation she found herself in demand for character parts like Cockney servant girls and drunken cooks.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 141ff" DBREF="68825">141ff</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Furbank 8" DBREF="10711">8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She also <JOB HISTORICALTERM="film actress" REG="acting">played in films</JOB>, though she said that getting a part for the cinema was, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I imagine, rather more difficult than getting into the Kingdom of Heaven, and certainly passing through the eye of a needle can be nothing to it.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 229" DBREF="68825">229</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She gives a spirited account of early film-making at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Elstree</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Hertfordshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> in the 1920s: how multifarious the activity of the studio, how hot the lights, how temperamental the mikes.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 229-34" DBREF="68825">229-34</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She said that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the longest and nicest engagement I ever had</QUOTE> was in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Ringer</TITLE> (presumably the play of that title by <NAME>Edgar Wallace</NAME>, which began its successful run in May 1926).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 179" DBREF="68825">179</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB on Jacob; on Edgar Wallace" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>The <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Oxford Dictionary of National Biography</TITLE> gives this date under Wallace but 1936, presumably in error, under Jacob.</P></SCHOLARNOTE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">IMDb</TITLE> lists NJ (wrongly calling her <SOCALLED>Jacobs</SOCALLED>) in only two film casts: those of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The First Born</TITLE>, 1928, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Glamour</TITLE>, 1931.</P><P>One stage part she hated playing was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">one of those foul-mouthed and golden-hearted old women, who drink, swear, steal, and in fact do everything but murder, and yet retain hearts as pure as the driven snow.</QUOTE> After she played a beefeater (with a Yorkshire accent) in <NAME STANDARD="Sheridan, Richard Brinsley">Sheridan</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Critic</TITLE> a pantomime manager, thinking she was a man, enquired about engaging her.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 210, 217" DBREF="68825">210, 217</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="VISITED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>She acted in Ireland during the Troubles, both at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Dublin City">Dublin</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Dublin"></REGION><GEOG REG="Ireland"></GEOG></PLACE> and at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Belfast</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Antrim"></REGION><GEOG REG="Northern Ireland"></GEOG></PLACE>, where there was violence in the streets and Catholic members of the touring company were advised to keep their religion a secret.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 156-9" DBREF="68825">156-9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS EROTIC="EROTICPOSSIBLY"><DIV2><HEADING>Loving Women</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ&apos;s close personal friends included <NAME>Henrietta Carlotta Francesca Maria Simeone</NAME> or <SOCALLED>Simmy</SOCALLED>, daughter of an Italian father and English mother. <LIVESWITH><NAME STANDARD="Simeone, Henrietta Carlotta Francesca Maria">Simmy</NAME>, a lifelong Londoner, shared NJ&apos;s Edgware Road flat.</LIVESWITH><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 252" DBREF="68825">252</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 124" DBREF="68930">124</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS><INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS EROTIC="EROTICYES"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>In the same sanatorium where she met a man whom she nearly married, NJ encountered <NAME>Olivia Etherington-Smith</NAME>, an upper-class woman with whom, after initial hostility on both sides, she began an affair which lasted for years. <LIVESWITH>Etherington Smith accompanied her to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Sirmione"></SETTLEMENT><GEOG>Italy</GEOG></PLACE> when she moved there, and stayed with her when their household became a m&eacute;nage &agrave; trois after it was joined by <NAME>Sadie Robinson</NAME> (whom, too, NJ met at a sanatorium, probably the same one). The three-way relationship produced plenty of rows, but Olivia met NJ&apos;s need for passion while Sadie allowed herself to be dominated.</LIVESWITH> After Jacob met Radclyffe Hall, she fell violently in love with Hall&apos;s companion, <NAME>Una Troubridge</NAME>, and the resulting emotional complications, as well as political disagreement, ended the friendship.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 134-5, 138-9, 147-51" DBREF="68930">134-5, 138-9, 147-5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS></DIV1><DIV1><FRIENDSASSOCIATES><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ wrote a letter of appreciation to <NAME>Radclyffe Hall</NAME> after <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Well of Loneliness</TITLE> appeared in 1928. In January the following year she met Hall and <NAME>Una Troubridge</NAME> when the former lectured in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Southend</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Essex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> (though she was not much impressed with the lecture). Hall and Troubridge visited Jacob at Sirmione in summer 1934, and when they returned the next year they brought with them the third party in the relationship, <NAME>Evgenia Souline</NAME>. The second visit was less successful. Jacob disliked Souline on sight (she was in some ways xenophobic, while Souline was antisemitic) and resented her on Troubridge&apos;s behalf. She also disliked the way that Hall and her satellites had espoused the cause of <NAME STANDARD="Mussolini, Benito">Mussolini</NAME>, whom she had already seen through.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 148-51" DBREF="68930">148-51</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The breach was later mended, however, and Jacob visited Hall when the latter was in hospital with her final illness.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 167" DBREF="68930">16, 167</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FRIENDSASSOCIATES></DIV1><DIV1><LEISUREANDSOCIETY><DIV2><HEADING>Cross-Dressing</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ claimed it was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">more practical and more economical</QUOTE> to dress in male clothes:<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="FC" DBREF="107913" QTDIN="QTDINYES"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> men&apos;s tailored suits, generally with a tie, and her hair cropped. (She wore a skirt to Mass.)<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 69" DBREF="68930">69</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She adopted a masculine manner to match. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Short, plump and moon-faced, with heavy horn-rimmed glasses, dressing in men&apos;s tailored suits and heavy masculine boots or brogues, she would speak in rich baritone tones, laying down the law right and left.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Furbank 8" DBREF="10711">8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> When her future biographer, <NAME>Paul Bailey</NAME>, first encountered her, he thought for a moment that she was <NAME>J. B. Priestley</NAME> (with whom she shared her Yorkshire accent).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 22" DBREF="68930">22</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LEISUREANDSOCIETY></DIV1><DIV1><FRIENDSASSOCIATES><DIV2><HEADING>More Friends</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ met <NAME>Charlotte Despard</NAME> during the days of the suffrage struggle, and later as an actress on tour visited her at <PLACE><PLACENAME>Roebuck House</PLACENAME> in <SETTLEMENT CURRENT="Dublin City" REG="Clonskeagh">Clonskeagh</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Dublin"></REGION><GEOG REG="Ireland"></GEOG></PLACE>, not long after Ireland became independent. The cabman driving her, on learning that she was indeed going to visit <SOCALLED>herself</SOCALLED> (since Despard was sharing the house with <NAME>Maud Gonne</NAME>, one may wonder who he meant), declined to take any payment (though he accepted a generous amount of drink-money as a gift). Despard was being watched by an English plain-clothes detective, whom she invited in for tea and bread-and-butter.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 64, 156-7" DBREF="68825">64, 156-7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>NJ said one of the greatest influences on her after her mother was the actress <NAME>Gladys ffolliott</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 174-6" DBREF="68825">174-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Her friends in the music-hall and the theatre included a roster of distinguished and less distinguished names, the former ranging from <NAME>Marie Lloyd</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Campbell, Beatrice Stella">Mrs Patrick Campbell</NAME> to <NAME STANDARD="Gielgud, Val">Val</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Gielgud, Sir John">John Gielgud</NAME>. She moved less in literary circles, though she goes out of her way to mention a few famous writers (all male) whom she met, and to praise <NAME>Beverley Nichols</NAME> and <NAME>Irene Rathbone</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 98ff, 236-7, 241-5, 247" DBREF="68825">98ff, 236-7, 241-5, 247</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 142-3" DBREF="68930">142-3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>In Italy she knew (though she seems not to have thought much of) the poet <NAME>Gabriele D&apos;Annunzio</NAME>. Her biographer says she was covertly in love with her friend the singer <NAME>Gina Cigna</NAME>. In Naples late in the second world war she met the young actor <NAME>Harold Lang</NAME>, who later made a practice of doing comic impressions of her appearance and mannerisms.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 152, 173-4, 168, 176-8" DBREF="68930">152, 173-4, 168, 176-8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FRIENDSASSOCIATES></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Pre-War Italy</HEADING><LOCATION RELATIONTO="MIGRATED"><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="SYS"><DATE VALUE="1930--" CERTAINTY="CERT">1930</DATE><CHRONPROSE>NJ moved from <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE> ten days after a doctor told her she should settle in Italy as the only means to beat her lung disease. After about a year in a hotel at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Sirmione</SETTLEMENT> on <REGION>Lake Garda</REGION> in North <GEOG REG="Italy">Italy</GEOG></PLACE>, she bought a villa there.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 269" DBREF="68825">269</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 139, 144" DBREF="68930">139,144</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>She was already accustomed to spending five or six weeks in Italy every summer. Her Pekinese moved with her. She called her house Casa Mickie.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 269" DBREF="68825">269</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION><LOCATION RELATIONTO="VISITED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>In the early years of her Italian life she made frequent visits back to England, especially <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><LEISUREANDSOCIETY><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>At Sirmione NJ entertained friends (with cooking which was emphatically English, non-Italian) and kept numbers of cats and dogs.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Furbank 8" DBREF="10711">8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LEISUREANDSOCIETY></DIV1><DIV1><INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS EROTIC="EROTICYES"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>After <NAME>Sadie Robinson</NAME>, her next major relationship was with <NAME>Marjorie Zamble</NAME>, a married woman with two children (according to the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Oxford Dictionary of National Biography">Oxford Dictionary of National Biography</TITLE>; <NAME STANDARD="Bailey, Paul">Paul Bailey</NAME> does not mention her).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS></DIV1><DIV1><HEALTH ISSUE="PHYSICAL"><DIV2><HEADING>More Health Issues</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>Within three years of moving to Italy NJ was told by a specialist that her tuberculosis was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[n]ot <SOCALLED>arrested</SOCALLED>, not <SOCALLED>improving</SOCALLED>, but cured.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 269" DBREF="68825">269</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>After a couple of years in Italy she remarked that she had always managed to keep fit without taking exercise, which she detested in any form. A serious operation at about the time of her mother&apos;s death threatened her life and kept her in hospital for eight weeks.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Jacob, Other People, 266" DBREF="68825">266</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 146" DBREF="68930">146</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></HEALTH><HEALTH ISSUE="FEMALEBODY"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>This operation <EMPH>may</EMPH> have been a hysterectomy, which Jacob does not specify.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 146" DBREF="68930">146</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></HEALTH><HEALTH ISSUE="PHYSICAL"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>During World War Two NJ went down with malaria while on the island of <PLACE><REGION>Sicily</REGION><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, and had a recurrence at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Bari</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 165, 167" DBREF="68930">165, 167</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Invalided home, she underwent another <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">nasty, stupid operation</QUOTE> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 167" DBREF="68930" QTDIN="QTDINYES">167</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></HEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><POLITICS><DIV2><HEADING>Italian Politics</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>Having at first been inclined to admire <NAME STANDARD="Mussolini, Benito">Mussolini</NAME>, NJ had by <DATESTRUCT CERTAINTY="C" VALUE="1935-07-"><SEASON VALUE="07" CERTAINTY="C">summer</SEASON> <YEAR VALUE="1935">1935</YEAR></DATESTRUCT> recognized his <POLITICALAFFILIATION MEMBERSHIP="MEMBERSHIPYES" INVOLVEMENT="INVOLVEMENTNO" REG="anti-Fascist"><ORGNAME STANDARD="Fascist Party">Fascist</ORGNAME> regime as hateful</POLITICALAFFILIATION>. This was a bold stance to adopt at this date for someone resident in <PLACE><GEOG>Italy</GEOG></PLACE>: <NAME>Una Troubridge</NAME> (a pro-Fascist) seems to have felt that Jacob was indiscreet in her open anti-Fascism.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 150" DBREF="68930">150</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></POLITICS></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>The Second World War</HEADING><LOCATION RELATIONTO="MIGRATED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>In response to <NAME STANDARD="Mussolini, Benito">Mussolini</NAME>&apos;s racial laws, which barred Jews from various kinds of employment, NJ left Italy. While <NAME>Olivia Etherington-Smith</NAME> and <NAME>Sadie Robinson</NAME> travelled from <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Sirmione</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Lake Garda"></REGION><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE> to England, she spent some time first at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>St Raphael</SETTLEMENT> in the south of <GEOG>France</GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 161-2" DBREF="68930">161-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN1="NATIONALINTERNATIONAL1" RELEVANCE1="COMPREHENSIVE1"><DATE VALUE="1939-08-" CERTAINTY="BY">Before August 1939</DATE><CHRONPROSE>NJ, a virtual refugee from <NAME STANDARD="Mussolini, Benito">Mussolini</NAME>&apos;s antisemitic regime, reached <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> from <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Sirmione</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Lake Garda"></REGION> in <GEOG REG="Italy">Italy</GEOG></PLACE> by way of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>St Raphael</SETTLEMENT> in the south of <GEOG>France</GEOG></PLACE> and <PLACE><REGION>Gibraltar</REGION><GEOG REG="Spain"></GEOG></PLACE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 161-2" DBREF="68930">161-2</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (14 December 1940): 627" DBREF="54246">(14 December 1940): 627</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>She travelled with a friend and two small children, forced to leave her dogs and cats behind,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive (14 December 1940): 627" DBREF="54246">(14 December 1940): 627</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">with nothing much except the clothes on her back.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><OCCUPATION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>In <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> in <DATE>August 1939</DATE> NJ <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY PHILANTHROPYVOLUNTEER="PHILANTHROPYVOLUNTEERYES" REG="charity performer">took part in a charity gala</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> at <ORGNAME REG="Victoria Palace" STANDARD="Victoria Palace">Victoria Palace Theatre</ORGNAME> in aid of humanitarian preparations for mitigating the effects of war. She impersonated, with great success, a male Canadian radio presenter, <NAME STANDARD="Levis, Carroll Richard">Carroll Levis</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 162" DBREF="68930">162</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>NJ went to work, displaying <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the energy of five women,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 162" DBREF="68930" QTDIN="QTDINYES">162</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> as a <TOPIC>Second World War</TOPIC> <JOB REG="lecturer">lecturer</JOB> with the <EMPLOYER><ORGNAME>Ministry of Information</ORGNAME></EMPLOYER>, a<JOB REG="welfare supervisor">welfare supervisor</JOB> with <EMPLOYER><ORGNAME REG="ENSA" STANDARD="Entertainments National Service Association">ENSA, the Entertainments National Service Association</ORGNAME></EMPLOYER>, and a <JOB>broadcaster</JOB> for the <EMPLOYER><ORGNAME REG="BBC Overseas Service" STANDARD="BBC">BBC Overseas Service</ORGNAME></EMPLOYER>. She got into trouble for wearing the unauthorized uniform of a defunct women&apos;s organization from the First World War (probably <ORGNAME STANDARD="Queen Alexandra&apos;s Imperial Military Nursing Service">Queen Alexandra&apos;s Nursing Corps</ORGNAME>) but won her point and continued to wear it. For ENSA she safely <JOB REG="military escort">escorted</JOB> heavy, expensive cinema equipment on a nightmare journey through war-torn Italy for delivery to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Brindisi</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, and was then reprimanded on grounds that this job was beyond the capacity of a woman. A less unreasonable reprimand came to her when another job, as a <JOB>welfare officer</JOB> at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Bari</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, required her to fill in weekly progress sheets, and she simply ignored them. In <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Naples</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE> she <JOB REG="lecturer">lectured</JOB>, <JOB REG="journalist">wrote articles and opera programme notes</JOB> (in English: a new departure for the <ORGNAME>San Carlo opera</ORGNAME>), <JOB REG="entertainer">entertained the entertainers</JOB>, and demanded respect from German prisoners of war.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 162-4, 166-7, 169-71" DBREF="68930">162-4, 166-7, 169-71</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>Briefly back in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> in 1944, she <JOB HISTORICALTERM="actress" REG="acting">returned to the stage</JOB> as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the mother of a troupe of performing acrobats in a stage adaptation of <NAME>Margery Sharp</NAME>&apos;s novel <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Nutmeg Tree</TITLE>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 167" DBREF="68930">167</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> In 1951 she <JOB REG="lecturer">lectured</JOB> on the history of the theatre (pouring scorn on <NAME STANDARD="Ibsen, Henrik">Ibsen</NAME> as new-fangled).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 178-9" DBREF="68930">178-9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She was later persuaded by <NAME>Harold Lang</NAME> to <JOB REG="radio performer">star in a surrealistic radio play</JOB>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Quest for Corbett</TITLE>, on which he collaborated with <NAME STANDARD="Tynan, Ken">Kenneth Tynan</NAME>. She took this part although her first reaction had been that she <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">didn&apos;t understand a bloody word of this <QUOTE DIRECT="N">avant-garde tripe</QUOTE>,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 180" DBREF="68930">180</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and even though the protagonist, an outsize, celebrity woman writer, was modelled on herself. The play was printed in 1960.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 180-1" DBREF="68930">180-1</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian Catalogue" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="TRAVELLED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ&apos;s travels for ENSA took in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Rabat</SETTLEMENT> in <GEOG>Morocco</GEOG><AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE>, <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Algiers</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Algeria"></GEOG><AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE>, and Sicily (where she fell ill and was sent to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Taormina</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Sicily"></REGION><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE> to recover). She travelled across an Italy where roads and bridges were destroyed and children were starving to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Brindisi</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE> in the west. From <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Bari</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE> she travelled on medical leave, by ship to Scotland and then by train from <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Glasgow</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Lanarkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="Scotland"></GEOG></PLACE> to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> (arriving in February 1944). Early the next year ENSA sent her to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Naples</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, then to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Milan</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, with a visit on the way to a war-depleted <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Sirmione</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 164-71" DBREF="68930">164-71</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> (where <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Samuelo</QUOTE> had been erased, as a Jewish name, from the gravestone of her dog Sammy). <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 171-2" DBREF="68930">171-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Back in Italy and London</HEADING><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>After the war NJ continued, as before, to live at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Sirmione</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE> and visit <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, though she became increasingly disgusted with postwar Britain. At the end of her life she moved out of Casa Mickie into a smaller house in Sirmione.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 175, 178-9, 182" DBREF="68930">175, 178-9, 182</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P><CHILDLESSNESS>With no children of her own,</CHILDLESSNESS> <CHILDREN NUMBER="1">NJ became godmother to at least one Italian child, who grew up to run a cafe and remember her with warm affection.</CHILDREN><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 97" DBREF="68930">97</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS EROTIC="EROTICPOSSIBLY"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Paul Bailey calls her final household in Sirmione another <FOREIGN REG="household of three" LANG="fr">m&eacute;nage &agrave; trois</FOREIGN> featuring herself, her new secretary <NAME STANDARD="Martin, Denise">Denise Martin or Martino</NAME>, and <NAME>Sara Turner</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 179, 181" DBREF="68930">179, 181</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS></DIV1><DIV1><POLITICS><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>NJ, formerly an ardent <POLITICALAFFILIATION MEMBERSHIP="MEMBERSHIPYES" REG="Socialist">socialist</POLITICALAFFILIATION>, blamed the decline of deference in postwar Britain not on social change but on the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Labour Party">Labour</ORGNAME> government. She adopted, in other words, the <POLITICALAFFILIATION INVOLVEMENT="INVOLVEMENTYES" REG="Conservative">Tory</POLITICALAFFILIATION> attitudes of her immediate forebears.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 175" DBREF="68930">175</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></POLITICS></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Death</HEADING><DEATH><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="SYS"><DATE VALUE="1964-08-27">27 August 1964</DATE><CHRONPROSE>NJ died at the age of eighty, at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Sirmione</SETTLEMENT> on <REGION>Lake Garda</REGION> in <GEOG REG="Italy">Italy</GEOG></PLACE>, where she had lived for upwards of thirty years.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bailey 182" DBREF="68930">182</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></DIV2></DEATH></DIV1><WORKSCITED><SOURCE>Unless otherwise noted, all information is from the FC</SOURCE><SOURCE>Bailey, Paul. Three Queer Lives. 2001.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Bodleian Catalogue.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Furbank, P. N. Escape of a Half-Naked Sailor. 2001.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Open Plaques.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Trefusis, Violet. Don&apos;t Look Round. 1953. dustjacket.</SOURCE></WORKSCITED></DIV0></BIOGRAPHY>